Runcorn has two shopping centres. The original shopping area was in the older part of the town on  High Street, Regent Street, and Church Street.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Town centres], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref>  This centre continues to exist, but with the coming of the new town, has declined.  There is a small supermarket and some specialist shops, but with a higher-than-average proportion of [[charity shop]]s and [[Take-out|take-away]] food outlets.  A small market has been rebuilt adjacent to the old town bus station.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/traditionalmarkets?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Markets], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref>  In the centre of the new town area [[Halton Lea]] (formerly Shopping City) is an enclosed [[shopping mall]] with an attached bus station.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/towncentres/haltonlea?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Halton Lea], accessed [[June 28]] [[2007]]</ref>  Adjacent to it is Trident Park containing shopping outlets and a cinema<ref name="cinema">[http://www.cineworld.co.uk/reservation/ChoixResa.jgi?CINEMA=12 Cineworld], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref> and further away is an [[ASDA]] supermarket.<ref>[http://www.asda.co.uk/corp/storelocator_frameset/storelocator_frameset.htm Asda Runcorn], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref>

==Landmarks and places of interest==
[[Image:Halton Castle.jpg|thumb|Halton Castle]]
The major landmark in the town is Halton Castle on the top of Halton Hill near the geographical centre of the town. Only ruins of the castle exist, but there are widespread views from the top of the hill.  The interior of the castle grounds is open at advertised times.<ref>[http://www.haltoncastle.org Halton Castle], accessed [[27 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  Incorporated in the castle walls is the Castle Hotel, which used to include a courthouse on the first floor.  Another landmark is Norton water tower, built of Runcorn sandstone, {{ft to m|112}} high, which holds 672,000&nbsp;imperial [[gallon]]s (3&nbsp;million [[litre]]s) of water and supplies water to Liverpool.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p162</ref>

An important historical site and the major visitor centre in the town is Norton Priory, a museum.  The site contains the remains of an ancient priory with adjacent gardens, formerly of a country house.  Nearby are a [[walled garden]], including a national collection of tree [[quince]]s, and an [[Icehouse (building)|ice house]].<ref>[http://www.rossbullock.co.uk Norton Priory 1], accessed [[27 March]] [[2007]]</ref><ref name="np2">[http://www.nortonpriory.org Norton Priory 2], accessed [[27 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

Much of the architecture of the town is undistinguished, but there are [[Listed buildings in Runcorn, Cheshire|listed buildings]] of some importance.  The listed churches are All Saints Parish Church and Holy Trinity Church in the centre of the older part of the town, St Mary's in Halton village, St John's in Weston, and Christ Church in Weston Point.  The oldest existing houses are the Seneschal's house in Halton village (1598), Weston Old Hall (1607), Brookfield Farmhouse (1691), and Halton Old Hall (1693).  Other outstanding houses include Runcorn Town Hall (formerly Halton Grange), Camden House and Cottage in High Street, and Bridgewater House near the Ship Canal.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/planning/forwardplanning/listedconservationareas/listedbuildings?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Listed buildings in Halton], accessed [[27 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

A [[war memorial]] to those who lost their lives in [[World War I]], [[World War II]] and in later conflicts is at the bottom of Moughland Lane.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', p218</ref>  There is a memorial in Castle Road, Halton village, commemorating residents of the village who served in the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]].

==Culture==
===Theatre and cinema===
''[[The Brindley]]'' is a theatre and arts centre which opened in 2004.  It is situated in the old town centre and named after [[James Brindley]], engineer of the adjacent Bridgewater Canal.  It contains a [[proscenium]] theatre seating 420 and a multi-purpose theatre seating 108, ''The Studio'', which doubles as a cinema.  There is an exhibition space for art installations, a small café, and multi-purpose rooms.  The theatre is owned and administered by Halton Borough Council which runs community events in the building.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/thebrindley/ The Brindley], accessed [[28 July]] [[2007]]</ref> A [[Multiplex (movie theater)|multiplex cinema]] run by [[Cineworld]] is in Trident Park.<ref name="cinema"/>
[[Image:Waterloo Hotel, Runcorn.jpg|thumb|left|Waterloo Hotel, aka ''The Archer'']]
===Filmography===
Runcorn has been used for the shooting of so many films and television programmes that it has been described as ''Woollywood'',<ref>{{cite web | last= Neild | first= Larry | title= Food for thought | publisher= Liverpool Daily Post | url= http://www.liverpooldailypost.co.uk/liverpool-news/regional-news/2007/08/28/food-for-thought-64375-19695301/ | accessdate= 2007-08-27}}</ref> combining the obvious reference to Hollywood with the dialect term [[woollyback]] sometimes used by people from Liverpool to describe those not from that city. Some of the sequences of the first two series of the [[BBC]] police drama ''[[Merseybeat (TV series)|Merseybeat]]'' were filmed in and around the town.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/drama/merseybeat/ BBC: Merseybeat], accessed [[30 March]] [[2007]]</ref> The BBC [[situation comedy]] ''[[Two Pints of Lager and a Packet of Crisps]]'' is set in Runcorn. External shots of the Waterloo Hotel in the area of High Street known as Top Locks (which is known in the show as ''The Archer'') appear as well. The [[opening credits]] show the Silver Jubilee Bridge and Halton Castle.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/twopints/ BBC: Two Pints], accessed [[30 March]] [[2007]]</ref> ''[[Drop Dead Gorgeous (TV series)|Drop Dead Gorgeous]]'', a four-part comedy drama on [[BBC Three]], was set in Runcorn.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/bbcthree/programmes/gorgeous/ BBC: Drop Dead Gorgeous], accessed [[30 March]] [[2007]]</ref> The interior of the Undercroft at Norton Priory has been used for locations in films.<ref name="np2"/>

===''The Runcorn Ferry''===
Before the building of Runcorn Railway Bridge and its attached footbridge, the only way to cross the Mersey at or near Runcorn Gap, other than by the dangerous method of [[Ford (crossing)|fording]], was by the ferry.  The ferry has a history going back to the 12th century.<ref>Starkey, ''Old Runcorn'', pp10&ndash;11</ref> The ferry was celebrated in the [[monologue]] entitled ''The Runcorn Ferry'', written by [[Marriott Edgar]] and popularised by [[Stanley Holloway]].  It includes the lines:
{{cquote|Per tuppence per person per trip…
Per trip or per part of per trip.<ref>[http://monologues.co.uk/Runcorn_Ferry.htm The Runcorn Ferry], accessed [[14 May]] [[2007]]</ref>}}

==Community facilities==
The main library is at Halton Lea with a branch library in Egerton Street in the old town centre (which includes the archives of the Runcorn & District Historical Society).<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/libraries/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: Libraries], accessed [[22 March]] [[2007]]</ref> Runcorn has two locations offering One Stop Shop facilities; Halton Lea Direct Link is in Halton Lea and Runcorn Direct Link is in Church Street in the old town area.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/communityandliving/haltondirectlink/nearestonestopshop?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: One-Stop-Shop locations], accessed [[17 May]] [[2007]]</ref>  Runcorn Direct Link also includes a [[Visitor center|Tourist Information Centre]].<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/tourism/touristinformationcentre?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Tourist Information Centre], accessed [[17 May]] [[2007]]</ref>

[[Image:Runcorn Hill 2.jpg|thumb|Runcorn Hill]]
Runcorn Hill Local Nature Reserve has been developed on the site of a quarry and consists of heathland. Adjacent to it is a park which includes a [[bandstand]], a [[Radio-controlled boat|model boating]] lake, and sports facilities.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/nature/content/localnaturereserves/runcornhilllnr/ Halton Borough Council:Runcorn Hill Nature Reserve], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref> Wigg Island is a [[nature reserve]] on a former industrial site.  The reserve is on an island between the Manchester Ship Canal and the River Mersey and consists of open spaces and woodland with [[bird hide]]s and pathways.  Murdishaw Valley is an area of [[ancient woodland]] to the east of the town between the Murdishaw housing development and the M56.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/nature/content/localnaturereserves/wiggisland/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Wigg Island], accessed [[28 July]] [[2008]]</ref> Rock Park is on the site of a quarry in the old town area and includes sports facilities.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/parksandopenspaces/parksinhalton/rockpark/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Rock Park], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref> Town Park is in the centre of the new town development and has a link to the north with Norton Priory.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/environment/parksandopenspaces/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council Parks, open spaces and countryside], accessed [[22 March]] [[2007]]</ref> Open areas in Runcorn form part of Mersey Forest, one of Britain's [[Community Forests in England|community forests]].<ref>[http://www.merseyforest.org.uk/ Mersey Forest], accessed [[22 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

Runcorn's hospital is Halton Hospital, which is administered by the North Cheshire Hospitals NHS Trust.  This hospital is undergoing change.  Originally planned as a [[Hospital#Types|District General Hospital]], it was never large enough to provide a full range of services.  Acute medical services have been transferred to Warrington Hospital. The plan is to provide non-emergency surgery and rehabilitation at Halton Hospital.<ref>[http://www.northcheshirehospitals.nhs.uk/ North Cheshire Hospitals NHS Trust], accessed [[28 March]] [[2007]]</ref> Halton Haven Hospice is in the Murdishaw area of the town.<ref>[http://www.haltonhaven.co.uk/ Halton Haven], accessed [[23 April]] [[2007]]</ref>  [[Primary care]] services are provided by the Halton and St Helens [[NHS Primary Care Trust|Primary Care Trust]]. In Runcorn [[general practitioner]] services are provided in five health centres and in one separate medical practice in Heath Road.  There are dental practices providing National Health Service and private dental care.<ref>[http://www.halton-health.nhs.uk/ Halton and St Helens PCT], accessed [[28 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

==Transport== 
[[Image:Runcorn Bridges.jpg|thumb|left|Runcorn railway bridge is on the left and Silver Jubilee (road) bridge on the right]]
There are two railway stations.  [[Runcorn railway station|Runcorn (mainline) station]] is on the Liverpool branch of the West Coast Main Line.  From this station, [[Virgin Trains]] run 15 trains daily on weekdays between Liverpool and London, and [[Central Trains]] run services between Liverpool and Birmingham.  [[Runcorn East railway station|Runcorn East station]] is on the Chester to Manchester line.  [[Arriva Trains Wales]] and [[Northern Rail]] run an hourly service to Chester, Warrington, and Manchester.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/railinformation/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: Rail information], accessed [[21 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

[[Bus rapid transit#Implementation in Europe|Busways]] are also available. These are for use by buses only.<ref name="nt"/> There are two bus stations, one in the old town centre and the other at Halton Lea.  Two companies provide local public transport services, [[Halton Transport]]<ref>[http://www.haltontransport.co.uk/ Halton Transport], accessed [[28 July]] [[2007]]</ref> and [[Arriva North West and Wales|Arriva]].<ref>[http://www.arriva.co.uk/arriva/en/business_activities/transport_services/overview_1/ Arriva], accessed [[28 June]] [[2008]]</ref>  Express coach services calling at Runcorn are provided between Hoylake via Liverpool and London and between Southport and Cambridge by [[National Express]].<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/businformation/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Bus information], accessed [[21 March]] [[2007]]</ref> Coach services are provided by Selwyns<ref>[http://www.selwyns.co.uk/about_set.html Selwyns], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref> and Anthony's Travel.<ref>[http://www.anthonys-travel.co.uk/ Anthony's Travel], accessed [[28 June]] [[2007]]</ref> Both companies have depots in the town.

Runcorn has a system of expressways diverting through traffic from the local roads.<ref name="nt"/>  This system links to the north by the A533 over the Silver Jubilee Bridge to Widnes and south Lancashire, to the northeast to Warrington by the [[A56 road|A56]], to the east to [[Northwich]] and north Cheshire by the A533, and to the southeast by the A557 to the [[M56 motorway|M56]] and to [[Frodsham]].  The M56 links to the [[M6 motorway|M6]] and, to the north of Widnes, the A557 links to the [[M62 motorway|M62]].<ref>[[Ordnance Survey]], ''Landranger'' 108, 109 and 117 maps</ref> The Silver Jubilee Bridge becomes congested at peak travel times. In the event of a breakdown or accident on the bridge, traffic in the area comes to a standstill.  To resolve this problem, a second crossing of the Mersey is planned, to be known as the ''Mersey Gateway''.<ref>[http://www.merseygateway.co.uk/ Mersey Gateway], accessed [[26 March]] [[2007]]</ref> There is a network of dedicated [[Segregated cycle facilities|cycleways]] in the town.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/publictransport/content/cycling/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: Cycling in Halton], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  Runcorn is {{mi to km|8}} from [[Liverpool John Lennon Airport]] and {{mi to km|22}} from [[Manchester Airport]].

==Education==
There are 29 [[primary school]]s in the town and one [[nursery school]] at The Grange. The four [[secondary education#United Kingdom|secondary schools]] are Halton High, St. Chad's Catholic High, The Grange, and [[The Heath School|The Heath]].  Two institutions, Halton College and Runcorn Sixth Form College, merged in 2006 to form the Riverside College Halton.  There is one [[special school]] in the town, Cavendish School.  There are opportunities for [[adult education]] in [[information technology]] at the Acorn Lifelong Learning Centre and at the Grange City Learning Centre.  Other courses for adults are held at different venues in the town.<ref>[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/educationandlearning/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: Education and Learning], accessed [[30 March]] [[2007]]</ref>

The achievement and attainment tables for 2006 show that the primary schools in the Halton Local Authority perform in English, mathematics, and science in [[Key Stage 2]] at levels close to the average for England.<ref>[http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/group_06.pl?Mode=Z&No=876&Base=p&Type=LA&Phase=p&Year=06  Dfes Primary Schools 2006], accessed [[4 July]] [[2007]]</ref>  The attainments of the secondary schools in the local authority are, however, below national levels.  Using the measure of 5 or more grades A*&ndash;C in the [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] (or equivalent), including English and mathematics, the average for England is 45.8% while the Halton average is 33.3%.  The figures for the individual secondary schools in Runcorn are Halton High 22%, St. Chad's Catholic High 39%, The Grange 24% and The Heath 42%.<ref>[http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/group_06.pl?Mode=Z&No=876&Base=b&Type=LA&Phase=1&Year=06 Dfes Secondary Schools 2006], accessed [[4 July]] [[2007]]</ref>

==Religion==
[[Image:Runcorn All Saints 1.jpg|thumb|150px|All Saints Parish Church]]
The 2001 [[census]] showed, that of the people living in the borough of Halton, 83.8% declared themselves to be [[Christian]], 8.7% stated that they had "no religion," and 7.0% made no religious claims at all. Those stating their religions as [[Buddhism|Buddhist]], [[Hinduism|Hindu]], [[Judaism|Jewish]], [[Islam]] or [[Sikhism|Sikh]] amounted to 0.5%.<ref>[http://www.statistics.gov.uk/StatBase/ssdataset.asp?vlnk=8920&Pos=4&ColRank=1&Rank=176 2001 census], accessed [[2 April]] [[2007]]</ref>

The [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] churches are part of the [[Diocese of Chester]] and the deanery of Frodsham.<ref>[http://www.chester.anglican.org/diocese/links/index.htm#Frodsham Frodsham deanery], accessed [[2 April]] [[2007]]</ref><ref name="church">[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/localinfo/placesofworship/churchesinruncorn/coe/?a=5441 Halton Borough Council:Churches in Runcorn], accessed [[2 April]] [[2007]]</ref>
In Runcorn the parish church is All Saints in the old town centre. There are ten more Anglican churches in the town.<ref name="church"/>  Five Roman Catholic churches can be found in Runcorn. They are administered by the [[Diocese of Shrewsbury]].<ref>[http://www.dioceseofshrewsbury.org/ Diocese of Shrewsbury], accessed [[2 April]] [[2007]]</ref>  There are three Methodist chapels and one [[Presbyterian Church of Wales|Welsh Presbyterian]] chapel.  Wicksten Drive Christian Centre is shared between the Church of England and the Methodists.  There is an [[Independent Baptist]] chapel, three independent Christian churches, and a [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]].   The [[Jehovah's Witnesses]] have two [[Kingdom Hall]]s, and there is a [[Spiritualism|Spiritualist]] church.<ref name="church"/>  There are no places of worship in Runcorn for any other major world religions.

==Sports==
Runcorn's main football club is [[Runcorn Linnets|Runcorn Linnets FC]]. This club has had a complicated history.  At one time, Runcorn F. C. played on a ground in Canal Street, Runcorn.  When this land was sold for housing in 2000, the team played at grounds outside the town and was renamed [[Runcorn F.C. Halton]].  In 2006 there was a change of management, and the team's name was changed again.  The club is in the [[North West Counties Football League|North West Counties League]] Division 2, and their home ground is shared with [[Witton Albion F.C.]] at Wincham Park Stadium in Northwich.<ref>[http://www.runcornfc.co.uk/ Runcorn Linnets FC], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  At the end of the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season, the club gained promotion to Division 1 of the League<ref>[http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Runcorn&action=edit&section=40 icCheshireOnline], accessed [[27 April]] [[2007]]</ref>. It is hoped that they will be able to play their home games in Runcorn starting next season.<ref>[http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/runcornandwidnesweeklynews/tm_method=full%26objectid=18970107%26siteid=50020-name_page.html Runcorn and Widnes Weekly News], accessed [[27 April]] [[2007]]</ref>  There are a number of smaller football clubs in the town for adults and children.

Runcorn Cricket Club and Runcorn Hockey Club are based at the Runcorn Sports Club in Moughland Lane.  Runcorn Rugby Union FC is based at Halton Sports Club in Murdishaw.  There is an 18 hole golf course at Runcorn Golf Club in Clifton Road<ref>[http://www.englishgolf-courses.co.uk/cheshire/runcorn.php Runcorn Golf Club], accessed [[25 April]] [[2007]]</ref> and a golf driving range at Sutton Fields.<ref>[http://www.suttonfields.co.uk/index.html Sutton Fields], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref>   Runcorn Sports Club is a privately run sports club in Moughland Lane and provides facilities and coaching for cricket and hockey. Halton Sports Club is in Murdishaw Avenue. There is a privately run swimming pool in Beechwood local centre and another at Stockham Lodge Raquet and Health Club. Adjacent to the latter are two [[artificial ski slope]]s administered by Runcorn Ski Centre.<ref>[http://www.runcornskicentre.co.uk/ Runcorn Ski Centre], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref> The Runcorn Rowing Club rows on the River Weaver Navigation near Clifton Village.<ref>[http://www.runcornrowingclub.org.uk/ Runcorn Rowing Club], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  Sports centres run by the local authority include Brookvale Recreation Centre, which has indoor sporting facilities, Phoenix Park, which has outdoor sporting facilities, and Runcorn Swimming Pool.<ref name="sports">[http://www2.halton.gov.uk/content/tourismandleisure/sports?a=5441 Halton Borough Council: Sports in Halton], accessed [[29 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  Facilities for other sports are also available.<ref name="sports"/>

==Notable people==
[[Image:Thomas Hazlehurst.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Thomas Hazlehurst,<br> chapel builder]]
Individuals from Runcorn who have gained entry into the [[Dictionary of National Biography#Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'']] include [[Sir John Chesshyre]] (1662&ndash;1738), a prominent [[lawyer]],<ref>Lemmings, David, 'Chesshyre, Sir John (1662&ndash;1738)', ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/5235], accessed [[7 March]] [[2007]]</ref>   [[Nathan Alcock]] (1707&ndash;79), a noted [[physician]],<ref>Moore, Norman, ‘Alcock, Nathan (1709–1779)’, rev. Caroline Overy, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, 2004 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/292], accessed [[1 March]] [[2007]]</ref> and his brother  [[Thomas Alcock (1709-1798)|Rev. Thomas Alcock]] (1709&ndash;98), Vicar of Runcorn, and writer and [[cider]] maker.<ref>Woodland, Patrick, ‘Alcock, Thomas (1709–1798)’, ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'', Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, Oct 2006 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/296], accessed [[1 March]] [[2007]]</ref>  [[Thomas Hazlehurst (businessman)|Thomas Hazlehurst]] (1779&ndash;1842) founded one of the two major [[soap]] and [[alkali]] manufacturing businesses in the town, [[Hazlehurst & Sons]].  His son [[Thomas Hazlehurst (chapel builder)|Thomas Hazlehurst]] (1816&ndash;76) was involved with the business. He was a [[Methodist]] who paid for the construction of 12 chapels and three schools in the area.<ref> Vardy, P. I. 'Thomas Hazlehurst and his family', ''Cheshire History'', 45:2005-2006.</ref>  

[[Edward John Smith]] (1850&ndash;1912), [[captain]] of the ''[[RMS Titanic|Titanic]]'',  purchased a retirement home in Higher Runcorn but never lived there because of his death aboard the Titanic. [[Hall Caine|Thomas Henry Hall Caine]] (1853&ndash;76), a [[novelist]] and [[playwright]], was born in Runcorn.<ref>Allen, Vivien, ''Hall Caine: Portrait of a Victorian Romancer'', Sheffield Academic Press, 1997. ISBN 1-85075-809-3</ref>  [[Thomas Alfred Jones]] (1880&ndash;56) was awarded the [[Victoria Cross]] and the [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]] during [[World War I]].<ref>Thompson, Dave.  ''I Laughed Like Blazes: The Life of Private Thomas 'Todger' Jones, VC, DCM'' Dave Thompson, 2002.</ref>  In more recent times the [[singer]] and [[actor|actress]] [[Kym Marsh]] (1976&ndash; ) and the actor [[Jack Ryder (actor)|Jack Ryder]] (1981&ndash; ) often spend their weekends in Runcorn with Marsh's family.<ref>[http://iccheshireonline.icnetwork.co.uk/0100news/0100regionalnews/tm_objectid=17001927&method=full&siteid=50020&headline=ex-hear-say-star-s-passion-for-runcorn--name_page.html Ex Hear'Say star's passion for Runcorn], ''Cheshire Online'', accessed [[12 November]] [[2006]]</ref>  The [[boxing|boxer]] [[Robin Reid]] (1971&ndash; ) attended secondary school in Runcorn, a place he identifies as his home town.<ref>[http://www.boxrec.com/boxer_display.php?boxer_id=5000 Robin Reid], accessed [[23 April]] [[2007]]</ref> The singer [[Nicola Roberts]] (1985&ndash; ) from the British girl band, '[[Girls Aloud]],' also comes from Runcorn.<ref>[http://www.nicolaroberts.net/page3/page3.html Nicola Roberts], accessed [[23 April]] [[2007]]</ref>

